      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φίλημα ἀγάπης",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Constit. ap.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ii. 57 (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὸ ἐν κυρίῳ φίλημα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); Tertullian, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "de orat.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 14 (osculum pacis). The brotherly kiss, the usual salutation of Christians, proceeded from the custom of antiquity, particularly in the East, to unite a salutation with a kiss. But Paul calls it ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἅγιον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", as a symbol of the holy Christian fellowship. In the Greek church it is still used at Easter.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
